    en: "RPAPL Article 9 (Sections 901-993) lets any co-owner of real property force a sale or physical division when the co-owners cannot agree. Co-owners as tenants in common or joint tenants (but NOT tenants by the entirety, for married couples) have the absolute right to partition. The action is filed in Supreme Court in the county where the property is located. The court orders either partition in kind (physical division — rare) or partition by sale (the usual remedy). Sale proceeds are distributed among co-owners per their ownership shares, with adjustments for contributions to expenses, improvements, and mortgage payments. Partition is often used after inheritance when heirs cannot agree on disposition or after unmarried couples separate."
